<!--         <p class="lead">Thank you for your interest in participating in the 2018 Stanford Night Market</p>
 -->        <h2>What is Stanford Night Market?</h2>
        <p>Stanford Night Market is an annual event hosted by the Taiwanese Cultural Society to celebrate Asian culture and community. There will be food, performances, and games, reminiscent of Taiwan’s vibrant nightlife. Night Market is also an opportunity to bring together the entire community, both student groups and members of the Bay Area. The Stanford Night Market is one of the many successful student-run night markets through the United States via the Intercollegiate Taiwanese-American Student Association.</p>
        <h2>Why participate in the Stanford Night Market?</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Largest night market event between Los Angeles and Seattle</li>
          <li>Targeted toward students and young adults</li>
          <li>Rapidly growing event with more than a 200% increase in attendance each year</li>
          <li>Low cost of entry without long term leases or expensive licenses</li>
          <li>Join an event that supports local businesses and entrepreneurs</li>
          <li>Be associated with an event showcasing local causes and talent</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#event-information" class="clickable" style="cursor: pointer">Event Information</h2>
        <div id="event-information" class="collapse in">
          <p><strong>Location:</strong> White Plaza, Stanford University — Stanford, California</p>
          <p><strong>Date and time:</strong> Saturday, April 14 from 5 to 8:30 pm. </p>
          <p><strong>Expected attendance:</strong> 1200-1600+ people</p>
        </div>

        <h2 data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#vendor-package-options" class="clickable" style="cursor: pointer">Vendor Package Options</h2>
        <div id="vendor-package-options" class="collapse in">
          <h3><strong>Prepaid package — $260</strong></h3>
          <i>Details:</i>
          <ul>
            <li>Includes 10’ x 10’ canopy tent, 8’ table, 2 chairs</li>
            <li>Temporary event health permit</li>
            <li>Requires free seller's permit registration</li>
            <li>Marketing in the South Bay and Peninsula</li>
            <li>Two 11" x 17" posters for marketing (More available upon request.)</li>
          </ul>
          <i>Best for:</i>
          <ul>
            <li>Vendors with staff available to sell food directly at the Night Market</li>
            <li>Vendors with large amounts of food available to bring to the event</li>
          </ul>
          <h3><strong>Bulk sales - no fee</strong></h3>
          <i>Details:</i>
          <ul>
            <li>Stanford student groups will directly purchase and pick up food in bulk at a discounted price from your restaurant; the amount of food will be determined by student groups</li>
            <li>All food must be prepared and packaged according to health regulations outlined below</li>
            <li>Student organizations are reserved the right to profits from reselling the food at the Night Market</li>
          </ul>
          <i>Best for:</i>
          <ul>
            <li>Vendors with fewer staff members and are unable to directly sell food at the Night Market</li>
            <li>Vendors interested in selling bulk quantities of easily transportable food</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <h2 data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#faq-text" class="clickable" style="cursor: pointer">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div id="faq-text" class="collapse in">
          <h4>What permits are needed?</h4>
          <p><strong>The vendor package includes a temporary event health permit. Additionally, please provide a copy of your restaurant facility permit and a temporary seller’s permit. California requires all vendors to apply for a temporary seller’s permit with the California Board of Equalization (a permit for sales of taxable items). Registration is free and can be done at <%= link_to 'https://efile.boe.ca.gov/ereg/index.boe', 'https://efile.boe.ca.gov/ereg/index.boe' %>. </strong></p>
          <!-- <p>A food sales permit will be provided as part of the package. <strong>No cooking is allowed on site. All food preparation must be performed at a health department approved commercial kitchen</strong> - we highly encourage preparing the food at your own facilities, then selling prepackaged food at the event for simplicity. <strong>Please provide a copy of your restaurant facility permit as well.</strong> This is required as part of the temporary health permit. Please note that potentially hazardous foods (e.g. meat, dairy) need to be kept below 45 degrees Fahrenheit or above 135 degrees Fahrenheit through heating elements or cooling containers.</p> -->

          <h4>What does the prepaid vendor package not include?</h4>
          <p>Vendors are responsible for their own chafing dishes and heating supplies, banners and signage, any additional tables.</p>

          <h4>Is there a certain way that food must be prepared?</h4>
          <p>No cooking is allowed on site. All food preparation must be performed at a health department approved commercial kitchen. Please note that potentially hazardous foods (e.g. meat, dairy) need to be kept below 45 degrees Fahrenheit or above 135 degrees Fahrenheit through heating elements or cooling containers. In accordance with health regulations of the state of California, food must be purchased and consumed within four hours of cooking/preparation even if the food is stored and reheated later.</p>


          <h4>Is there a certain way that food must be served?</h4>
          <p>All food must be individually packaged (in a sealed bag, box, or other container) prior to the event, in a certified facility (e.g. approved commercial kitchen). All packaged food must have a label for the time at which it was packaged, and must be purchased and consumed within four hours of that timestamp.  No food can be in open containers or exposed to air until after it has been sold to consumers.</p>

          <h4>Will there be a space for waste disposal?</h4>
          <p>Stanford Night Market provides general waste disposal. Dumping oil or other cooking materials onto grass or public spaces is strictly prohibited.</p>

          <h4>Are alcohol sales allowed?</h4>
          <p>Alcohol sales are not allowed at the Stanford Night Market.</p>

          <h4>How should items be priced?</h4>
          <p>Prices should reflect reasonable market rates. Night markets are known for having great bargains, and customers are price sensitive. We recommend selling in volume at lower prices. The Stanford Night Market reserves the right to set a maximum price as necessary.</p>



